[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The **1878–79 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between June 3, 1878, and September 3, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 46th United States Congress convened on March 18, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections were held for all 293 seats, representing 38 states.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the last election cycle that at least one state held its regular congressional election in an oddnumbered year.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] These elections occurred in the middle of President Rutherford B.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] With a sour economy as the nation's pressing issue, both major parties lost seats to the new Greenback Party, which was established to promote the long-term use of paper money as a solution to stop enormous economic fluctuations.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The Democratic Party remained the largest party, but lost its majority.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] However, it allied with several independent politicians and was able to remain in power.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the fourth and last recorded House election where both major parties lost seats at the same time.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In most states, the elections were held November 5, 1878.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In 1845, Congress set a uniform nationwide date for choosing presidential electors.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This Act of Congress did not affect election dates for Congress, which remained within the jurisdiction of state governments, but over time, the states moved their congressional elections to this date as well.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] California's elections were the last time a state held congressional general elections after November.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections are listed by date and district.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Patterson successfully contested the election and was seated March 4, 1877.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In the 2nd district the difference between the two candidates, in the initial returns, was just 22 votes.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Bisbee challenged Hull's election, and was eventually awarded the seat on January 22, 1881.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] South Carolina was rampant with voter fraud, particularly through the use of tissue ballots, thin ballots hidden in the normal ballot, typically 10 to 20 at a time.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] The almost statewide exclusion of Republicans as Commissioners of Elections, and the ensuing appointment of nearly all Democratic Managers of Elections, allowed to Democratic Managers to perpetrate this scheme.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] When the votes were counted and more votes than voters were found, the Managers removed and destroyed the Republican ballots resulting in the complete takeover of the state.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Wisconsin elected eight members of congress on Election Day, November 5, 1878.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The **1878–79 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1878 and 1879, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The Democratic Party recaptured control of the Senate for the first time since before the Civil War.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In these elections, the winners were seated in 1879 before March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In these regular elections, the winners were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1885; ordered by state.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In this election, the winner was elected in 1879 after March 4.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] James Black Groome was elected by a margin of 60.22%, or 56 votes, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In New York, the election was held on January 21, 1879, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Republican Roscoe Conkling had been re-elected in January 1873 to this seat, and his term would expire on March 3, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] At the State election in November 1877, 19 Republicans and 13 Democrats were elected for a two-year term (1878–1879) in the State Senate.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] At the State election in November 1878, 97 Republicans, 28 Democrats and 3 Greenbackers were elected for the session of 1879 to the Assembly, and Republican Thomas Murphy was elected to fill the vacancy in the State Senate caused by the death of Democrat John Morrissey.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The 102nd New York State Legislature met from January 7 to May 22, 1879, at Albany, New York.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The caucus of Republican State legislators met on January 20, Temporary President of the State Senate William H.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Present were all Republican legislators except State Senator Louis S.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Goebel (6th D.) and Assemblyman James W.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The caucus of the Democratic State legislators met also on January 20.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Ecclesine (8th D.) offered to adopt a prostest against the senatorial election proceedings, claiming that the senatorial and assembly districts were incorrectly apportioned and thus the State Legislature did not represent the wish of the people of the State.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The protest was substituted by a resolution to appoint a committee which would elaborate an address on the apportionment at a later date.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Ecclesine then marched out, and the remaining legislators nominated Lieutenant Governor William Dorsheimer for the U.S.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The two Greenback assemblymen John Banfield (Chemung Co.) and George E.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Williams (Oswego Co.) voted for 87-year-old Peter Cooper, a New York City inventor, industrialist and philanthropist who had run for U.S. president in 1876 on the Greenback ticket.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Roscoe Conkling was the choice of both the Assembly and the State Senate, and was declared elected.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Note: The votes were cast on January 21, but both Houses met in a joint session on January 22 to compare nominations, and declare the result.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] In Pennsylvania, the election was held January 20, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Donald Cameron was re-elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the United States Senate.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Simon Cameron resigned from office, his son J.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] Donald Cameron was elected by the General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, in 1877 to serve the remainder of the unexpired term, which was to expire on March 4, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1879-united-states-senate-election-in-colorado] The Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on January 20, 1879, to elect a Senator to serve the term beginning on March 4, 1879.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The **1880 United States House of Representatives elections** were held for the most part on November 2, 1880, with five states holding theirs early between June and October.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] They coincided with the 1880 presidential election which was won by James A.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Garfield, who was a member of the House at the time.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections were held for 293 seats of the United States House of Representatives, representing 38 states, to serve in the 47th United States Congress.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the first time that every state held their regular House elections on or before Election Day.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Special elections were also held throughout the year.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Issues such as Civil War loyalties, tariffs, graft and corruption dominated the year's elections, though none became substantive as a national issue.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The economy was growing stronger after emerging from a long Depression.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] It was in this political environment that Garfield's Republican Party gained 19 seats and regained control of the House from the Democratic Party.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The Greenback Party, an emerging party of workers and farmers, also lost seats in these elections, after gaining more than a dozen two years earlier.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In 1880, no states held their elections after Election Day for the first time (California was the last state to hold late elections, in 1878).
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Maine held elections for its five members on September 13, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Ohio held elections for its twenty members on October 12, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Oregon held its election early on June 7, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Texas held elections for its six members on June 1, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Vermont held elections for its three members on September 7, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/1880-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Wisconsin elected eight members of congress on Election Day, November 2, 1880.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Enacted as Article 18, section 16 of the state constitution, the law addresses "personal use and regulation of marijuana" for adults 21 and over, as well as commercial cultivation, manufacture, and sale: regulating marijuana in a manner similar to alcohol, namely for recreational use.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Possession and cultivation of marijuana became legal on December 10, 2012, after governor John Hickenlooper issued an executive action adding Amendment 64 to the state constitution.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The commercial sale of marijuana to the general public began on January 1, 2014, at establishments licensed under the regulatory framework.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] As of April 2017, 176 of Colorado's 272 municipalities have opted to prohibit retail marijuana activity within their boundaries.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Proposed initiative 2011/12 #30 was submitted on January 4 and found sufficient by the Secretary of State on February 27 to appear on the general ballot for the November election.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Consumption is permitted in a manner similar to alcohol, with equivalent offenses prescribed for driving under the influence.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The new legislation does not apply to medical marijuana.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The amendment provides for licensing of cultivation facilities, product manufacturing facilities, testing facilities, and retail stores.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Local governments can now regulate or prohibit such facilities.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The B.E.S.T. program assists in renovation, repairs, and new school construction needs for Colorado public schools.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] B.E.S.T. receives funding from state land tax proceeds, lottery proceeds, interest tax proceeds, and marijuana sales tax proceeds via Amendment 64.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The Colorado Department of Education annual B.E.S.T. reports suggest that Amendment 64 has provided a visible increase in funding to this program.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Since implementation of Amendment 64, the Colorado B.E.S.T. program has seen a decrease in overall annual applications numbers, an increase in overall granted applications numbers, and an increase in cash granted amounts since implementation of Amendment 64 in 2014.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The largest survey for the amendment, conducted October 23, 2012 by Public Policy Polling, indicated that 53% of voters intended to support it, with 46% opposed.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On December 9, 2013, more than a year after the passing of Amendment 64, a Public Policy Polling poll showed that the majority of Coloradans still support legal marijuana.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] With 53% support versus 38% opposition, the survey of 928 Colorado voters showed little change in support for legal marijuana a year on from the amendment vote.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Since the amendment passed there has been concern over its conflict with federal substance prohibition laws.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The outcome is nevertheless expected to have broad impacts south of the border, including in Mexico where less than a week after the U.S. vote Mexican senators submitted a proposal to legalize marijuana in their country.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Though support for liberalizing drug policy has traditionally been considered a liberal or libertarian cause, Amendment 64 garnered a number of high-profile conservative endorsements, including, most notably, an endorsement from former U.S.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Representative and 2008 Republican Presidential Candidate Tom Tancredo, who claimed, "Throughout my career in public policy and in public office, I have fought to reform or eliminate wasteful and ineffective government programs.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] There is no government program or policy I can think of that has failed in such a unique way as marijuana prohibition." Similarly, Temple Emmanuel's Rabbi, Steven Foster, endorsed Amendment 64 because, "as clergy, we have the responsibility to talk about what policies serve our community best.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] You do not have to use marijuana—or even approve of marijuana—to see that our current laws are not working." Many supporters of Amendment 64 did so because they wanted to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the state's law enforcement resources.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Proponents believe that permitting recreational use will allow officers to focus on prevention of violent crime and that it will remove some of the burden on the state's prosecutors and courts.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The campaign also points out that teens who currently seek marijuana have to turn to criminals for their supply and that these criminals may expose teens to other, potentially more dangerous drugs like heroin, meth, or cocaine.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Supporters also point out that Colorado's experience with medical marijuana supports their conclusion: The CDC's Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance System monitors a number of statistics for America's youth.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The CDC study suggests that marijuana use among Colorado's youths fell by 2.8 percent from 2009 (24.8 percent) to 2011 (22 percent), while the national rate of youth use increased by 2.3 percent from 2009 (20.8 percent) to 2011 (23.1 percent).
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Furthermore, the CDC found that the availability of drugs on school grounds in Colorado fell 5 percent from 2009 (22.7 percent) to 2011 (17.2 percent), while the national rate increased by 3.1 percent over the same time.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The group "No on 64" objected to Amendment 64 chiefly because it claimed the amendment would lead to increased use of marijuana, a consequence the group considers harmful.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On October 14, *The Denver Post'*s editorial board announced its opposition to Amendment 64.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The policies took effect when the Governor ratified the ballots, which was to happen within 30 days of the election.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Governor John Hickenlooper officially added the law to the state's constitution on Monday December 10, 2012 making the private consumption of marijuana legal in Colorado.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The first stores officially opened on January 1, 2014.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] John Hickenlooper stated "This will be a complicated process, but we intend to follow through.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On March 13, 2013, the task force issued 58 recommendations on how recreational pot should be grown, sold and taxed in the state.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On May 28, 2013, Governor Hickenlooper signed several bills into law implementing the task force's recommendations.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On September 9, 2013, the Colorado Department of Revenue adopted final regulations for recreational marijuana establishments, implementing the Colorado Retail Marijuana Code (HB 13-1317).
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On September 16, 2013, the Denver City Council adopted an ordinance for retail marijuana establishments.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] These local licensing requirements are in addition to the state licensing requirements.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On May 28, 2013 the government also proposed Proposition AA, a 15% excise tax on the "average market rate" and a 10-15% sales tax on retail sales (on top of the 2.9% state sales tax and any local government sales taxes).
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] *The Denver Post* disagreed, citing the insufficiency of licensing fees to previously regulate medical marijuana and rejecting the notion that the taxes would drive pot back to the black market.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On November 5, Proposition AA was approved by a wide margin, as were similar local taxes such as a 3.5% Denver marijuana sales tax which is on top of the 3.62% Denver sales tax.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The provisions of Amendment 64 concerning personal use are not affected by the local bans on retail sales, so that growing and possession of small quantities of "personal" pot are legal statewide under state (but not federal) law.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Most localities have chosen to ban retail stores, at least temporarily.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Colorado Springs is the county seat of El Paso county, the second most populous county in the state.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] A tiny majority of El Paso county voters approved the statewide Amendment 64 with an original margin of only 10 votes.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In Colorado Springs the measure won by just 2% favored by only 5,000 out of more than 200,000 ballots cast.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Relying on the local option clause in the amendment, the city council then voted 5-4 not to permit retail shops in the city.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Some council members expressed concern over the effect pot shops would have on existing businesses, as well as on local military bases.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Current mayor John Suthers, elected in May 2015, supports the ban on pot shops; his opponent in the mayoral election supported recreational pot shops as a way to increase city tax collections.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Suthers, a former Colorado Attorney General, has long been an outspoken opponent of legalized marijuana.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Retail marijuana outlets are also banned in unincorporated areas of El Paso County.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] As of 2016, the only area in El Paso County to permit retail recreational marijuana outlets is the city of Manitou Springs, which adjoins Colorado Springs to the west, and has two retail recreational pot shops, the maximum number allowed by city ordinance.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Medical marijuana outlets continue to operate in Colorado Springs although current regulations prevent any new stores from opening.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] As of 2015, there were 91 medical marijuana clinics in the city, which reported sales of $59.6 million in 2014, up 11 percent from the previous year.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In Pueblo County in 2013 the commissioners adopted laws governing the recreational marijuana industry.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The laws allows for the establishment of recreational marijuana grows, manufacturing, testing and retail facilities.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The county currently limits the industry to 15 retail marijuana stores which produced more than one half million dollars in taxes in their first year.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In 2014 the citizens adopted a tax measure designed to fund college scholarships.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In April 2016 a citizen group, operating under Amendment 64's local option, is threatening to bring the issue to ballot with the potential outcome that if adopted the established industry would be forced to shut down anywhere it operates within the unincorporated county.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] County Commissioner Sal Pace said if this ban were to pass it would hurt the county.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In 2015 the county generated a net revenue of $1.75 million from recreational marijuana sales.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In February 2015, the state of Colorado reported that tax collection figures for 2014, the first year of legal commercial sales, reached a total of $44 million from recreational marijuana with a further $32 million collected from fees on the industry and pre-existing taxes on medical marijuana.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The projected revenue before legalization was $60 million.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] These sales and excise tax figures do not include the corporate and personal income taxes generated by businesses and employees working in the state's marijuana industry.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The state Department of Revenue reported that official sales of recreational and medical marijuana from dispensaries reached over $996 million in 2015; a $297 million increase from the $699 million sold in 2014.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The 2015 sales alone generated $135 million of tax revenue, $35 million of which are being used for the Education Center construction projects.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Colorado has experienced significant financial benefit as a result of legalization, with marijuana tax, license and fee revenue surpassing $1 billion as of 2019.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] This revenue has been used to finance youth, education and health programs; the first $40 million of annual fee revenue is used to repair and upgrade local elementary schools and education facilities.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] Colorado has seen an 8% rise in homelessness since legalization, which has fueled speculation as to whether increased marijuana use is partially to blame; however, this rise is likely attributed to migration into the state as a result of legalization, including those who were already homeless.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The number of teenagers sent to emergency rooms with THC-positive substance screens more than quadrupled after marijuana was legalized.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The state also saw a 3% increase in car collision claims after legalization.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] In 2015, Nebraska and Oklahoma attempted to file suit in federal court to stop the implementation of Amendment 64, claiming that Colorado cannabis was harming their localities, and should be preempted by federal law.
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] If their effort prevailed, it could have "potentially [led] to all state-level legalization laws being struck down".
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] The United States Solicitor General filed an amicus brief urging the bill of complaint not to be heard, in layman's terms "urging the court to stay out of the case".
[src:2012-colorado-amendment-64/2012-colorado-amendment-64] On March 21, 2016, the United States Supreme Court denied Nebraska and Oklahoma's motion, leaving Amendment 64 and other states' legalization laws in effect.
